# Typography Scale — Luxury Brand Standard

All font sizes across the website MUST follow this hierarchy. These values mirror the typographic scale used by luxury brand sites (e.g., Chanel) for readability and visual hierarchy.

## Heading Sizes

| Level | Usage | Mobile | Desktop |
|-------|-------|--------|---------|
| H1 | Hero / Primary headings | 36px | 48px |
| H2 | Secondary headings | 28px | 36px |
| H3 | Sub-section headings | 24px | 30px |
| H4 | Section titles / labels | 20px | 24px |

## Body Text Sizes

| Usage | Size |
|-------|------|
| Paragraph / body text | 16px – 18px |
| Small text / secondary captions | 14px – 16px |
| Fine print / disclaimers | 12px – 14px |

## Navigation / UI Elements| Usage | Size |
|-------|------|
| Nav links (mobile) | 14px – 16px |
| Nav links (desktop) | 16px – 18px |
| Buttons / CTAs | 14px – 16px |
| Labels / tags | 12px – 14px |## Rules

1. **Never** use font sizes smaller than 12px anywhere on the site.
2. Headings must use the scale above — do not use arbitrary sizes like 8px, 9px, 7px for visible text.
3. Use responsive sizing: smaller values for mobile (< 768px), larger values for desktop.
4. Prefer `rem` or `px` units. Tailwind classes like `text-sm`, `text-base`, `text-lg`, etc. are acceptable.
5. The font family remains `"Helvetica Neue", Helvetica, Arial, system-ui, sans-serif` unless otherwise specified.